Andrea is coming in early for the conference and will be in the office this=20
Wednesday.   Based on our conversation a few weeks ago I thought you might=20
want the following information on the requirements for a foreign attorney to=
=20
be licensed in Texas.  (I have not mentioned anything to Andrea regarding=20
this issue.)  The requirements for a Texas license are set forth in the Texa=
s=20
Board of Law Examiners Rule XIII B.

The requirements include:

1.  Having been licensed, for at least five of the last seven years, to=20
practice law in the highest court of the foreign nation.
2.  Hold the equivalent of a J.D. degree (Texas requires that the applicant=20
must use an approved credential evaluation service to evaluate the applicant=
s=20
legal education.)
3.  Meet one of the following:
 A.  Demonstrate that the law of such foreign nation is sufficiently=20
comparable to the law of Texas that, in the judgment of the board, it enable=
s=20
the foreign attorney to become a competent attorney in Texas without=20
additional formal education, or
 B.  hold an L.L.M. from an approved Law School.


The University of Houston offers a general comparative L.L.M. program that i=
s=20
open to foreign students.  The program take anywhere from one year to three=20
years depending on whether the student is going full time or part time. =20
Applicants must present evidence of a high grade point average or class=20
standing at the undergraduate law level.

Enron offers educational assistance and will reimburse employees for up to=20
90% of the costs of courses and 75% of the costs of required books for=20
work-related courses of study.  Reimbursements are made upon successful=20
completion of approved courses.

